This paper presents a novel approach to reinforcement learning that focuses on transfer learning and improving generalization. The paper discusses the use of a shared representation space and decoupling the learning of task representation, forward dynamics, inverse dynamics, and reward function. These concepts are all related to machine learning and artificial intelligence, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of this approach for online planning, which is related to robotics and control systems, suggesting that it may also belong to the cs.RO (Robotics) and cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-categories. Finally, the paper presents empirical results in both continuous and discrete RL domains, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category, as RL is often used in computer vision applications.
